00:21:15,201 --> 00:21:15,681
We don't know.

197
00:21:17,824 --> 00:21:29,357
So he says that you have to be careful when somebody talks to you about it, when he talks, that you can distinguish between what's experiential and what's actually being inferred.

198
00:21:29,878 --> 00:21:29,959
Hmm.

199
00:21:33,449 --> 00:21:38,234
The next one, again, is really just talking about specious reasoning, silly reasoning.

200
00:21:39,056 --> 00:21:48,209
So it's a reflection on appearances, which refer to theories such as, it's got here as an example, the Big Bang Theory.

201
00:21:48,628 --> 00:21:50,250
So that is a theory.

202
00:21:51,553 --> 00:22:01,886
There can't be, I don't think, any absolute decision about that because it begs the question as to why it happened in the first place.

203
00:22:02,625 --> 00:22:09,556
So it always goes back to this original point where, okay, there was this explosion, but hey, why?

204
00:22:09,977 --> 00:22:10,798
Where has it come from?

205
00:22:11,459 --> 00:22:14,564
Because nothing comes of nothing, to quote wonderful Shakespeare.

206
00:22:16,686 --> 00:22:24,499
So it's that sort of reflection you have to be careful of.

207
00:22:25,086 --> 00:22:48,698
there's also this business about you've thought about something you've actually gone through the whole process but again it says there's a bias towards a notion and that's what we're not always aware of is aware of our biases right so biases these days you get the word bias being used as opposed to prejudice a prejudice is something that you you're quite aware of

208
00:22:49,066 --> 00:23:18,448
but a bias is a sort of way of looking and I gave a talk a couple of weeks back on the way that we as a culture receive Buddhism through our biases unknown to us we're not fully aware of the fact that we're always judging the Buddha's teachings always reframing it in terms of science or in terms of the romantic movement

209
00:23:18,951 --> 00:23:32,451
The whole idea of being at one with nature, you get Buddhist writers talk about, well, eventually what we want is this beautiful oneness with everything, you know, which is actually a romantic idea.

210
00:23:33,273 --> 00:23:37,160
There's nothing that I know of in the scriptures about the oneness with nature.

211
00:23:37,759 --> 00:23:46,073
It's always about getting your morals right and really discovering this other transcendent experience of nirvana.

212
00:23:46,998 --> 00:23:55,269
Not that you don't have those experiences, but it's definitely not where Buddhism has got its teachings towards.

213
00:23:55,810 --> 00:23:58,694
If they arise, all well and good, but that's not the purpose.

214
00:23:58,714 --> 00:24:02,800
That would also be another transitory state, as the Romantics pointed out.

215
00:24:02,840 --> 00:24:06,967
You could get blissed out in nature one day, and then the next day it rained.

216
00:24:10,772 --> 00:24:12,414
So you can't hold it.

217
00:24:13,761 --> 00:24:17,566
So you've got to be careful of these biases that we're not aware of.

218
00:24:18,688 --> 00:24:20,250
And how do you become aware of them?

219
00:24:20,269 --> 00:24:21,750
Well, that's another good question.

220
00:24:21,770 --> 00:24:23,513
How do you become aware of your biases?

221
00:24:24,454 --> 00:24:28,519
And it's through really discussing these things with people who have different views.

222
00:24:29,119 --> 00:24:39,211
So that was something else that comes out very clearly in, say, the American election, where on the surface of things, it looked as though Clinton had it made.

223
00:24:39,714 --> 00:24:58,505
But then there were all these, I mean, Facebook is especially criticized for it, that people were really only reading their own little group, you know, just reestablishing, cementing their views and opinions as a group and therefore weren't listening at all to anybody else.

224
00:24:58,986 --> 00:25:01,690
And when the election came, of course, it was all a big surprise.

225
00:25:04,538 --> 00:25:09,104
So you have to be careful about agreement after pondering views.

226
00:25:10,244 --> 00:25:13,450
Obviously it has to have an appropriate base to it, you see.

227
00:25:16,773 --> 00:25:20,858
One thing that seems to be missed in this is intuition.

228
00:25:21,539 --> 00:25:22,961
You know, this sort of gut feeling.

229
00:25:24,584 --> 00:25:29,230
That sort of feeling of being right or being wrong.

230
00:25:29,497 --> 00:25:59,013
you get people saying things like I feel and it annoys people who say I think because people who say I feel have an intuitive grasp of it but can't often explain why and people who say I think want to know why and people who say I think annoy people who say I feel because often their thinking isn't right according to their feeling according to the way they've intuited something

231
00:25:59,652 --> 00:26:08,362
I remember little arguments arising out of that separation at Gaia House around the coordinator, what we'd call the managers at the time.

232
00:26:09,663 --> 00:26:10,743
I feel, I think.

233
00:26:12,625 --> 00:26:16,871
But you can't trust your intuition either, because you don't know where you're coming from.

234
00:26:17,711 --> 00:26:24,078
Just because you have an intuition that something is right or wrong, it still has to be tested, you still have to question it.

235
00:26:25,279 --> 00:26:28,983
Your intuitions also are based upon a bias.

236
00:26:29,268 --> 00:26:32,452
An internal bias with which we're looking at the world.

237
00:26:32,772 --> 00:26:41,307
I mean, in terms of the spiritual life, our fundamental biases are, you know, that happiness is to be found in this world, in the sensual world.

238
00:26:41,948 --> 00:26:44,451
That things have some sort of permanency.

239
00:26:44,491 --> 00:26:48,979
That I have a sense of me that is permanent, even though everything else is changing.

240
00:26:49,159 --> 00:26:50,601
You know, that's the problem with the self.

241
00:26:51,289 --> 00:27:05,786
So these more deluded, deeper biases, delusions are actually biasing the way that we experience life, creating perhaps expectations that aren't possible.

242
00:27:10,210 --> 00:27:15,576
The final one is to do with the teacher.

243
00:27:17,210 --> 00:27:22,817
It's just really having too much faith in the teacher and what seems probable.

244
00:27:23,317 --> 00:27:30,045
So, I mean, that's an interesting one because generally you have to have a certain confidence in your teacher, you know.

245
00:27:31,086 --> 00:27:39,656
And it's interesting because when you, if anything happens whereby you lose confidence in the teacher, the whole thing is actually snapped.

246
00:27:39,957 --> 00:27:41,359
I remember it happened to me.

247
00:27:41,400 --> 00:27:48,095
I, you know, I had a teacher who I had a lot of admiration for and all that and et cetera, et cetera.

248
00:27:48,115 --> 00:27:53,686
And then he did something and just something snapped and I thought, no, this, this guy won't do.

249
00:27:53,747 --> 00:27:58,557
And I left, you know, I went, I went, I went somewhere else.

250
00:27:59,396 --> 00:28:01,679
And it wasn't that he was evil or anything.

251
00:28:01,940 --> 00:28:03,701
I just lost confidence in him.

252
00:28:03,721 --> 00:28:17,316
And it's not that I didn't go back and stay with him and form a good relationship with him, but it was as though something had sort of snapped my faith in him, which might have been a good thing.

253
00:28:17,516 --> 00:28:19,278
I mean, you know, it's not...

254
00:28:19,298 --> 00:28:23,301
Sometimes you do over...

255
00:28:23,321 --> 00:28:25,724
I mean, you can't help...

256
00:28:25,958 --> 00:28:32,647
I don't think you can help giving your teacher an order that they don't actually have.

257
00:28:34,329 --> 00:28:37,173
Because you're always looking to them for advice and whatnot.

258
00:28:37,795 --> 00:28:52,215
And there's always that tendency to see them as slightly more enlightened, better, more ethical, etc., etc., than they actually are.

259
00:28:52,777 --> 00:28:55,881
And when they trip, you think, oh, blood and sand, I'm not going to.

260
00:28:59,167 --> 00:29:02,806
You're probably doing it to me, you see.

261
00:29:02,885 --> 00:29:06,765
I'm preparing for you to say, what the bloody hell's going on?

262
00:29:07,420 --> 00:29:08,981
So it's just one of those things.

263
00:29:09,001 --> 00:29:09,643
You can't help it.

264
00:29:09,663 --> 00:29:12,086
But everybody does it to anybody who leads.

265
00:29:12,185 --> 00:29:14,409
I mean, that's the whole point of a leader, isn't it?

266
00:29:14,429 --> 00:29:21,618
They sort of surround themselves with this charisma, which isn't something that they may have particularly developed.

267
00:29:21,858 --> 00:29:23,701
People have dumped it on them.

268
00:29:23,862 --> 00:29:25,203
I've actually seen them like that.

269
00:29:25,703 --> 00:29:27,286
And it's very blinding, you see.

270
00:29:27,787 --> 00:29:29,429
And the Buddha wouldn't have any of that, too.

271
00:29:29,469 --> 00:29:33,714
There's a lovely bit just as he's dying where there's a young monk...

272
00:29:34,605 --> 00:29:43,396
who's looking upon him with the eyes of adoration, and he sends him off into the forest to go and meditate.

273
00:29:43,416 --> 00:29:46,902
So it's just a wrong sort of relationship.

274
00:29:46,922 --> 00:29:56,913
So he's very clear about what the relationship of a teacher and a student should be, that the student should be constantly questioning the teachers.

275
00:29:56,933 --> 00:30:04,443
I mean, obviously following the directions as best they can, but then never being completely taken in.

276
00:30:08,760 --> 00:30:10,125
You'll probably all be leaving tomorrow.

277
00:30:15,584 --> 00:30:20,339
So anyway, if we now just read on, you see.

278
00:30:22,008 --> 00:30:25,336
So he made this statement about what not to believe.

279
00:30:25,797 --> 00:30:26,838
But he doesn't leave it there.

280
00:30:27,440 --> 00:30:29,684
Remember, these people aren't...

281
00:30:29,704 --> 00:30:31,429
This is probably the first time they've seen him.

282
00:30:32,230 --> 00:30:33,253
They don't know him very well.

283
00:30:33,273 --> 00:30:39,207
They've heard this rumour, this reputation that he has, but they don't know him.

284
00:30:39,186 --> 00:30:41,951
So he starts right from the beginning.

285
00:30:41,990 --> 00:30:43,553
He says, what do you think, Calamas?

286
00:30:43,633 --> 00:30:47,638
Does greed appear in a man for his benefit or harm?

287
00:30:48,098 --> 00:30:49,621
It's for his harm, venerable sir.

288
00:30:50,663 --> 00:30:57,952
Being given to greed, being overwhelmed and vanquished mentally by greed, this man takes life, steals, commits adultery and tells lies.

289
00:30:58,292 --> 00:31:01,217
He prompts another to do so, to do likewise.

290
00:31:01,617 --> 00:31:03,701
Will that be long for his harm or ill?

291
00:31:05,403 --> 00:31:06,865
For his ill, venerable sir.

292
00:31:08,869 --> 00:31:14,259
And then he goes on the same sort of process about hate.

293
00:31:14,539 --> 00:31:19,730
So there's greed, there's hate, and will that be long for his harm and ill?

294
00:31:20,090 --> 00:31:21,613
Well, yes, Venerable Sir.

295
00:31:21,633 --> 00:31:22,935
And what do you think of delusion?

296
00:31:22,996 --> 00:31:26,863
You see, overwhelmed by delusion, he takes life, steals, etc.

297
00:31:27,344 --> 00:31:30,169
So that's also not so very good.

298
00:31:30,519 --> 00:31:32,020
Are these things for good or bad?

299
00:31:32,060 --> 00:31:33,363
They're bad, Venerable Sir.

300
00:31:33,423 --> 00:31:35,163
Blameable or not blameable?

301
00:31:35,284 --> 00:31:36,505
Blameable, Venerable Sir.

302
00:31:36,625 --> 00:31:38,606
Censured or praised by the wise?

303
00:31:39,208 --> 00:31:46,094
So here, you see, he's not saying you can make up your own mind about things, you can have your own thoughts and go your own way.

304
00:31:46,513 --> 00:31:50,518
This business of blameable and praised by the wise constantly comes up in his teaching.

305
00:31:50,778 --> 00:32:00,527
So you have to actually find out what somebody whom you see as more...

306
00:32:00,507 --> 00:32:28,994
trustworthy or more advanced than yourself in terms of morals and spiritual life and to be able to to take that advice undertaken and observed do these things lead to harm or ill or not and how does it strike you undertake and observe these things lead to harm and ill this is how it strikes us therefore i say and then it repeats that formula do not you know just believe somebody because of this and this and that

307
00:32:32,586 --> 00:32:34,009
And then, of course, he says the opposite.

308
00:32:34,628 --> 00:32:43,358
So when there isn't greed, and a person does not take life, does not steal, etc., etc., will that be long for his benefit and happiness?

309
00:32:43,719 --> 00:32:44,660
Yes, venerable sir.

310
00:32:45,141 --> 00:32:46,722
And then he does the same process.

311
00:32:46,782 --> 00:32:53,009
Remember, this is the oral tradition, so it's all put in a particular way so you can actually remember it.

312
00:32:53,089 --> 00:32:55,511
So there are phrases spoken over and over again.

313
00:32:56,053 --> 00:32:59,416
So again, hate, will that be long for his benefit?

314
00:32:59,497 --> 00:33:00,498
No, no, definitely not.

315
00:33:00,518 --> 00:33:02,559
And then the same with delusion, okay?

316
00:33:02,539 --> 00:33:11,028
So these people don't know him, and he's giving them a way to find out whether something is beneficial or not for them.

317
00:33:11,388 --> 00:33:18,195
And he's giving them something that they can relate to immediately, which is greed, hatred, aversion, and delusion.

318
00:33:20,157 --> 00:33:31,450
So then, of course, and finally to sum it all up, he says, when these things are taken, is that for good or bad, undertaken, observed, these things lead to benefit and happiness.

319
00:33:31,597 --> 00:33:32,785
And this is how it strikes us.

320
00:33:34,031 --> 00:33:35,238
And then he repeats this.

321
00:33:35,500 --> 00:33:37,329
Then there's a repetition of that formula.

322
00:33:37,369 --> 00:33:39,481
Don't believe anybody because of this and that.

323
00:33:39,884 --> 00:33:50,740
But now, having sort of laid down a sort of moral platform by which they can decide whether something is good or bad, he then tells them how to live.

324
00:33:51,643 --> 00:34:02,500
So a disciple of the noble ones, Kalamas, in this way, devoid of coveting, that's the greed, devoid of ill will, undiluted, clearly comprehending and mindful...

325
00:34:02,732 --> 00:34:32,436
dwells having pervaded with the thought of amity of love one quarter likewise the second the third the fourth like we do in the evening and so above and below and across he dwells pervade he dwells having pervaded all the existence of all living beings everywhere the entire world with the great exalted boundless thought of love that is free of hatred and malice so now he's telling them how to actually practice in his daily life

326
00:34:32,905 --> 00:34:41,085
And then he goes, he says the same thing with compassion, the same thing with joy and the same thing with equanimity.

327
00:34:41,166 --> 00:34:47,420
So there you've got your four illimitables, something that you can actually develop in your ordinary daily life.

328
00:34:47,907 --> 00:35:07,565
So having laid down a sort of moral platform that we should be doing what is a benefit to us and to ourselves and to others, he then gives a practice whereby you would support that sort of attitude, which is developing love, compassion, joy and peacefulness.

329
00:35:10,588 --> 00:35:16,293
And he says when you get to this, he says you get these four consolations, four solaces.

330
00:35:18,028 --> 00:35:36,193
So when a disciple of the noble ones has such a hate-free mind, such a malice-free mind, such an undefiled mind, such a purified mind, there is one of the four consolations or solaces are to be found here.

331
00:35:37,574 --> 00:35:39,418
Suppose there is a hereafter.

332
00:35:39,958 --> 00:35:41,099
Suppose there's an afterlife.

333
00:35:41,637 --> 00:35:53,255
and there is a fruit, result of deeds done well or ill, then it is possible that at the dissolution of the body after death, I shall arise in the heavenly world which is possessed of the state of bliss.

334
00:35:53,576 --> 00:35:55,018
This is the first consolation.

335
00:35:56,199 --> 00:35:58,563
Supposing there is no hereafter, right?

336
00:35:58,583 --> 00:36:00,286
So there's no after...

337
00:36:00,487 --> 00:36:27,016
there's no afterlife and there is no fruit no result of deeds well done or ill yet in this world here and now free from hatred free from malice safe and sound and happy i keep myself so this is the second consolation so even if there's even if you even if you drop dead and that's the end of it at the end of life practicing like this at least brings you a certain level of happiness in this very life

338
00:36:28,954 --> 00:36:37,952
And in the same way, or in the opposite way rather, supposing evil befall an evildoer, I think of doing evil to no one.

339
00:36:38,893 --> 00:36:40,737
Oh no, what's this?

340
00:36:42,280 --> 00:36:45,005
Oh yeah, supposing evil befall an evildoer.

341
00:36:45,666 --> 00:36:48,070
I, however, think of doing evil to no one.

342
00:36:48,652 --> 00:36:51,536
Then how can it affect me who has done no evil?

343
00:36:51,922 --> 00:36:59,730
So in other words, there's a sort of presumption there that if you're not committing evil, it's less likely for evil to come towards you.

344
00:37:00,570 --> 00:37:07,179
So obviously, if you're a sort of very angry sort of person, then you might find somebody who's actually more angry than you.

345
00:37:07,199 --> 00:37:09,081
And then you're stuck.

346
00:37:10,983 --> 00:37:19,532
This doesn't mean, of course, evil doesn't approach us, but there's a consolation there that you won't excite somebody's hatred towards you.

347
00:37:21,806 --> 00:37:46,954
supposing evil results do not befall an evildoer then I see myself purified in any case so because I don't do evil and there are consequences because I don't do evil then evil won't come to me if there is no consequence to evil then that's fine

348
00:37:46,934 --> 00:37:50,418
Because I don't do evil, no consequences will come to me.

349
00:37:50,980 --> 00:37:58,532
So here he's arguing about fate and about free will and we'll come to that towards the end.

350
00:38:04,139 --> 00:38:06,664
So these are the four solaces.

351
00:38:08,585 --> 00:38:12,291
And, of course, he says the opposite with doing good, yeah?

352
00:38:13,072 --> 00:38:19,621
So we can expect that we'll have good results from a moral life.

353
00:38:19,641 --> 00:38:29,476
Now, of course, at the end, they're all absolutely gobsmacked by the Buddha and they end up saying, Marvellous, Venerable Sir, marvellous.

354
00:38:30,277 --> 00:38:37,309
As if, Venerable Sir, a person who were to turn face upwards what is upside down or to uncover the concealed...

355
00:38:37,525 --> 00:38:44,333
or to point the way to one who is lost, or to carry a lamp in the darkness, thinking those who have eyes will see visible objects.

356
00:38:44,773 --> 00:38:49,039
So has the Dharma been set forth in many ways by the Blessed One.

357
00:38:49,059 --> 00:38:54,865
We, Venerable Sir, go to the Blessed One for refuge, to the Dharma for refuge, to the community for refuge.

358
00:38:55,266 --> 00:39:01,333
Venerable Sir, may the Blessed One regard us as lay followers who have gone for refuge for life from today.

359
00:39:01,653 --> 00:39:03,376
So he obviously had a big effect.

360
00:39:05,257 --> 00:39:06,840
So to sum up the

361
00:39:07,242 --> 00:39:23,405
the discourse to the Kalamas, remember that they don't know the Buddha, or they don't seem to know him, and he's not going to try and convert them, he's going to try and help them to discover for themselves what is wholesome for them and not.

362
00:39:23,425 --> 00:39:28,032
So first of all, remember he asks these questions about basically the moral life.

363
00:39:28,934 --> 00:39:30,715
Is something wholesome or unwholesome?

364
00:39:31,597 --> 00:39:33,300
And then once he's done that,

365
00:39:33,871 --> 00:39:59,219
he then goes on to explain about greed hatred and delusion well that's part of it really and then what happens when they're not there and then of course he says like once you've got your moral life going then you've got to develop these four qualities the four brahma viharas the illimitables love compassion joy and peacefulness but you could extend that of course to any virtue

366
00:40:00,364 --> 00:40:29,307
and then of course there are the four consequences consolations or solaces of how they're behaving so if there is a future life they'll get the benefit of good behaviour and even in this life so even if there isn't a future life then in this very life they'll get the benefit of a moral life so that's basically the teachings of this particular discourse and it's only

367
00:40:29,677 --> 00:40:54,873
right at the end do they actually accept the buddha as their teacher presumably after that or shortly after that at least on the next visit he would hit them with the four noble truths a four path and so on so skillful teaching these sorts of things are repeated in various scriptures throughout things so uh what does this um particular discourse tells us it tells us to be um

368
00:40:55,597 --> 00:41:17,688
very discriminative about what we actually hear or read or see and there's not only to use our own understandings our own intellect and understanding but also this accent upon what others think too so there's always that sense of relationship that you're not isolated

369
00:41:18,360 --> 00:41:24,132
But then, as Gandhi pointed out, the truth can be in a minority of one.

370
00:41:24,152 --> 00:41:26,878
So it really is a bit dodgy.

371
00:41:28,963 --> 00:41:39,204
The other thing I wanted to very quickly talk about was this lovely book called The Art of Thinking Clearly by Rolf Dobelli, the Swiss artist.

372
00:41:39,690 --> 00:41:41,333
Just certain things he says in it.

373
00:41:41,393 --> 00:41:42,715
I've just mentioned one or two here.

374
00:41:43,155 --> 00:41:45,918
How we believe something because of authority bias.

375
00:41:46,179 --> 00:41:51,226
These are all little phrases that psychologists have conjured up.

376
00:41:51,246 --> 00:41:53,768
So that's why they put film stars in all these products.

377
00:41:54,289 --> 00:41:56,331
Even though the film stars probably never use them at all.

378
00:41:56,813 --> 00:42:04,483
But because this film star ended up using this toothpaste, well, it must be good.

379
00:42:04,733 --> 00:42:14,547
The news of certain newspapers, you know, if you've got a bias towards the left or right in whatever you read, then that newspaper is giving you the correct news.

380
00:42:15,568 --> 00:42:17,090
There's also social proof.

381
00:42:17,110 --> 00:42:18,652
That's another little one of these phrases.

382
00:42:19,012 --> 00:42:24,159
So if somebody else believes it, then, you know, if you've got a crowd of you believing the thing, it must be right.

383
00:42:26,012 --> 00:42:46,333
This awful thing that's happening with Buddhists and Muslims, first of all in Burma, in Myanmar, really stoking up a real sort of irrational hatred, seems to now be happening in Sri Lanka, which is absolutely awful.

384
00:42:46,751 --> 00:42:52,259
And it's just a hard core of nationalists who have this idea that Sri Lanka ought to be Buddhist and all that.

385
00:42:52,278 --> 00:42:54,742
And there's been race riots and stuff.

386
00:42:54,842 --> 00:43:00,349
They've pulled out what they call emergency measures.

387
00:43:00,648 --> 00:43:04,273
The army's out on the streets to stop people attacking Muslims.

388
00:43:04,693 --> 00:43:07,257
And they're about 7% of the population as well.

389
00:43:10,260 --> 00:43:11,021
But that's what happens.

390
00:43:11,081 --> 00:43:12,503
You have this bias.

391
00:43:12,563 --> 00:43:14,646
You look for people who agree with you.

392
00:43:14,726 --> 00:43:16,168
You have your rationality.

393
00:43:16,570 --> 00:43:17,371
And then off you go.

394
00:43:17,413 --> 00:43:20,521
And we live in an age of extremes at the moment.

395
00:43:23,650 --> 00:43:27,202
There's also this business of, well, it's cognitive error, really.

396
00:43:27,222 --> 00:43:29,347
That's what they call this bias, cognitive error.

397
00:43:30,391 --> 00:43:36,737
There's things like neglect of probability overridden by magnitude.

398
00:43:37,157 --> 00:43:41,242
So, for instance, just the bias towards the lottery.

399
00:43:41,762 --> 00:43:47,389
The lottery gives you millions if you win, but the national savings only give you a million.

400
00:43:48,369 --> 00:43:51,273
But you get your money back.

401
00:43:51,293 --> 00:43:55,858
And yet people pour their money into the lottery because it's big money.

402
00:43:56,210 --> 00:43:56,831
It's weird.

403
00:43:57,311 --> 00:43:58,472
I mean, and you lose it.

404
00:43:58,692 --> 00:44:01,434
As soon as you give your partner the lottery, that's it, you've lost.

405
00:44:01,914 --> 00:44:09,902
But if you were to put it with Ernie, I think everybody's forgotten about Ernie, but in my younger days, he was big, Ernie.

406
00:44:11,702 --> 00:44:12,264
That's what you did.

407
00:44:12,324 --> 00:44:15,887
You put your money in national savings and you knew your money was there.

408
00:44:16,206 --> 00:44:17,427
They just used the interest.

409
00:44:17,949 --> 00:44:21,251
And okay, you don't get millions and millions, but you could get a million.

410
00:44:21,572 --> 00:44:22,733
And there were smaller prizes.

411
00:44:22,753 --> 00:44:24,173
And I won once, 100 quid.

412
00:44:25,414 --> 00:44:25,574
See?

413
00:44:28,153 --> 00:44:30,496
I was very fortunate because I crashed my brother's car.

414
00:44:33,820 --> 00:44:37,423
It was actually true, that.

415
00:44:37,443 --> 00:44:39,746
Oh, dear me.

416
00:44:39,766 --> 00:44:42,849
So, yes, oh, and there's this lovely gambler's fallacy.

417
00:44:42,889 --> 00:44:48,215
That's a nice one, where you think, well, you know, something good's got to happen.

418
00:44:48,737 --> 00:44:51,059
I can't be having bad luck all the time.

419
00:44:51,079 --> 00:44:54,262
But probability actually says you could be having bad luck all the time.

420
00:44:56,369 --> 00:44:58,873
He also mentions the problems with gut feelings.

421
00:44:58,932 --> 00:45:00,255
They're not to be coloured.

422
00:45:00,275 --> 00:45:02,117
And our emotions colour ourselves.

423
00:45:02,177 --> 00:45:06,143
A lovely story I heard about this divorce settlement.

424
00:45:06,164 --> 00:45:13,576
And this man, he was being told by somebody who comes here, who's a solicitor.

425
00:45:14,637 --> 00:45:17,061
And he was told, he said, look, you'll lose the case.

426
00:45:17,802 --> 00:45:18,864
You will lose the money.

427
00:45:18,903 --> 00:45:21,027
There is no way you're going to win it and everything.

428
00:45:21,579 --> 00:45:23,402
But he wanted to do it anyway.

429
00:45:23,422 --> 00:45:28,628
You know, just driven by, I suppose, hatred and some sort of twisted revenge.

430
00:45:30,269 --> 00:45:34,855
So his emotions just wouldn't let him see the sheer impossibility of what he was trying to do.

431
00:45:37,016 --> 00:45:39,900
The other one he points out is too much choices.

432
00:45:40,079 --> 00:45:45,106
Well, I'm sure you've all had that when you go along the biscuit racks at the supermarket.

433
00:45:45,126 --> 00:45:48,869
You know, you always end up with your favourites anyway, chocolate biscuits or something.

434
00:45:50,436 --> 00:45:51,918
There's overconfidence.

435
00:45:52,320 --> 00:45:53,882
My belief's better than you.

436
00:45:53,902 --> 00:45:59,268
Well, that, of course, comes down to what the Buddha called conceit, where you're always comparing yourself.

437
00:45:59,309 --> 00:46:00,369
That's the problem with the self.

438
00:46:00,851 --> 00:46:02,934
The self is always, remember, unsafe.

439
00:46:03,894 --> 00:46:14,369
So it either says it's better than somebody else, or it feels safer by saying an inferiority complex, where you say, well, you know, I'm not as good as you.

440
00:46:14,389 --> 00:46:14,789
I know that.

441
00:46:16,170 --> 00:46:27,387
And then there's that one about being equal, which is just a very subtle way of saying, well, my group is better than anybody else's or worse than anybody else's.

442
00:46:27,407 --> 00:46:35,358
There's also things about miracles giving meaning to happenings which don't have any real basis.

443
00:46:35,838 --> 00:46:37,280
Now, I don't know.

444
00:46:37,300 --> 00:46:42,128
The story around Constantine, who converted to Christianity...

445
00:46:43,018 --> 00:46:49,418
just before the big battle where his troops were completely outnumbered by the opposition in front of Rome there.

446
00:46:49,438 --> 00:46:51,425
He was attacking Rome.

447
00:46:51,505 --> 00:46:56,842
He had this dream, it seems, of a cross.

448
00:46:57,547 --> 00:47:04,878
So he must have been listening to the Christian preachers who were around at the time.

449
00:47:05,380 --> 00:47:07,242
This is the 4th century, right?

450
00:47:07,262 --> 00:47:16,536
So there was lots of religions in those times, as you know, or at least there was one major understanding about polytheism.

451
00:47:16,516 --> 00:47:42,202
and christianity was battering the way there and it seems as though he had a dream with this cross some some sort of cross with a cross in the middle of it and so he woke up with the presumption that this was going to win him his battle so he had everybody painted on their shields and he and he won and then he thought well i'm a christian after all and that was it it's a weird story how the whole of history can be changed to a dream and the empowerment that you give to a dream

452
00:47:44,443 --> 00:47:47,947
So, yes, that brings us to the end of that.

453
00:47:48,648 --> 00:47:53,635
And just as a side topic is, of course, the whole thing about free will.

454
00:47:54,135 --> 00:47:56,958
How free is the will?

455
00:47:57,519 --> 00:48:00,583
Well, it's not really exercised the East very much.

456
00:48:00,603 --> 00:48:04,728
There are, of course, people who've talked about conditioning and all that.

457
00:48:04,748 --> 00:48:06,570
But the West is really caught up in it.

458
00:48:07,090 --> 00:48:11,056
And if I'm right, you'd have to do your own little research.

459
00:48:11,076 --> 00:48:12,898
It all goes back really to St. Augustine.

460
00:48:13,367 --> 00:48:18,096
Saint Augustine argued that God created human beings to love him.

461
00:48:18,617 --> 00:48:22,864
Now, you can't condition somebody to love you and feel really good about it, right?

462
00:48:22,885 --> 00:48:26,170
You feel really good about somebody who out of their free will loves you.

463
00:48:27,413 --> 00:48:31,360
So he gave everybody the free will to love him or not.

464
00:48:31,728 --> 00:48:34,733
Which in Christian terms is really about morals.

465
00:48:35,313 --> 00:48:39,199
It's about, you know, because that's what Moses brought down from the mountain.

466
00:48:39,219 --> 00:48:43,728
He brought down a set of rules whereby people could live peacefully together.

467
00:48:46,152 --> 00:48:48,014
But it's exercised our philosophers a lot.

468
00:48:48,231 --> 00:48:59,498
And you get, I think Jean-Paul Sartre said something to the point that you are free to make any decision, but you're either too afraid to do it or too stuck in a rut.

469
00:49:00,199 --> 00:49:04,670
But you're actually free to make that decision as a conscious choice.

470
00:49:06,641 --> 00:49:10,846
And then you get people who are fatalists, you know, that just thinks you've no choice at all.

471
00:49:11,626 --> 00:49:13,268
Similar things happening in the Buddha's time.

472
00:49:13,289 --> 00:49:23,358
There were people who said that it didn't matter whether you went down the Ganges one way with great acts of love and the other way murdering and thieving and all that.

473
00:49:24,119 --> 00:49:27,842
Eventually it was just all conditioned and there were no consequences.

474
00:49:27,882 --> 00:49:29,844
It just happened.

475
00:49:32,306 --> 00:49:35,130
So free will...

476
00:49:35,414 --> 00:49:47,179
What's been argued by Buddhist writers, or most Buddhist writers, is what they call a compatibilist position, where yes, you are conditioned, but you do have a measure of free will.

477
00:49:49,538 --> 00:49:59,309
If you think of the path, I mean, people talk about the spiritual path and the Buddha talks about the path and he says it's an ancient path.

478
00:49:59,889 --> 00:50:15,547
So now, if you go on a walk and you're walking along a path and you come to a fork or something, you tend to get out your map to make sure you're going the right way and you consult the map and then you go off on that way.

479
00:50:16,347 --> 00:50:18,650
If as you go along you think, oh, you've misread the map,

480
00:50:18,900 --> 00:50:44,250
then you come back to the crossroad and you go the other way so there's a choice you know because because of our delusion there's a choice the choices come up because we're deluded because we don't actually know the path but that's all that is it's not as though the Buddha was unconditioned as a human being he still was conditioned so we can see from

481
00:50:44,568 --> 00:50:52,898
Me Chi Kiao, that she still sees these leftover traces in the mind of greed, hatred and delusive thinking.

482
00:50:53,498 --> 00:50:54,300
See?

483
00:50:54,320 --> 00:50:55,961
So it's not as though they've gone.

484
00:50:56,342 --> 00:50:59,567
And she would have behaved in a conditioned way.

485
00:50:59,626 --> 00:51:06,815
She'd have got up in the morning, gone for her alms round, sat down, etc., etc., had talks about the Dharma with the nuns, and so on and so forth.

486
00:51:07,255 --> 00:51:12,583
So it's not as though you become completely...

487
00:51:13,541 --> 00:51:20,454
This psychophysical organism that is working in society, etc., etc., becomes unconditioned.

488
00:51:20,514 --> 00:51:22,099
That's not the unconditioned bit.

489
00:51:22,760 --> 00:51:24,001
That's always going to be conditioned.

490
00:51:24,543 --> 00:51:34,302
Our job is, as the Buddha points out in the Kalama discourse, is to get those habits which are going to bring us just a natural happiness, a natural ease with life.

491
00:51:34,855 --> 00:51:37,603
The unconditioned is pointing to something else.

492
00:51:37,724 --> 00:51:41,856
It's pointing to that which doesn't belong to this order of things.

493
00:51:42,478 --> 00:51:47,835
But there's nothing there.

494
00:51:48,726 --> 00:51:54,916
The Nibbanic experience is one which is so transcendent of this life that it's completely empty of it.

495
00:51:55,538 --> 00:51:57,762
So that's what he means by this sunyata.

496
00:51:57,782 --> 00:52:03,871
It's empty of anything that we gain from this psychophysical organism.

497
00:52:04,773 --> 00:52:10,742
And it's that which is the unconditioned, and that's why it doesn't have any suffering.

498
00:52:10,762 --> 00:52:15,510
That's why it's a perfect blissful state, even though there's no emotions.

499
00:52:16,621 --> 00:52:23,623
So all these words that we use are all anchored in our actual living day-to-day life.

500
00:52:24,286 --> 00:52:30,224
But what he's saying is that there is something which is just simply not of this order.

501
00:52:31,706 --> 00:52:36,994
And the process of getting there is not the process of free will, of choosing.

502
00:52:37,353 --> 00:52:38,655
Yes, there are choices.

503
00:52:38,755 --> 00:52:40,938
The main thing is discernment.

504
00:52:40,958 --> 00:52:51,791
It's actually looking at what we're doing and questioning everything we do to see whether it's bringing us a natural happiness of this life or unhappiness.

505
00:52:53,373 --> 00:53:00,903
And then to begin to start seeing things from these three vantage points of desire, impermanence, not self.

506
00:53:01,322 --> 00:53:03,985
And slowly but surely there's an awakening.

507
00:53:04,367 --> 00:53:04,586
Right?

508
00:53:04,686 --> 00:53:06,248
That's the best word of all.

509
00:53:06,588 --> 00:53:13,878
A slow awakening of something in us which doesn't belong to this phenomenal world.

510
00:53:17,081 --> 00:53:17,882
And that's it folks.

511
00:53:19,965 --> 00:53:22,547
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

512
00:53:23,068 --> 00:53:25,771
That they have not caused even greater confusion.

513
00:53:25,811 --> 00:53:30,637
And that by your devotion to the spiritual life you will

514
00:53:30,954 --> 00:53:41,572
Relieve yourself of all suffering sooner rather than later.

